          "body": "The hymn's final line (v. 12) holds both rejoicing and warning: *rejoice, O heavens… woe to the earth and the sea, because the devil has come down to you, having great wrath, knowing that he has only a short time*. The dragon's fury is precisely calibrated to the shortness of his window. The remainder of the chapter (vv. 13-17) traces his earthly campaign: he pursues the woman, but she is given eagle's wings (Exodus 19:4) and flown to the wilderness for the same 3½ years. He spews a river from his mouth; the earth itself swallows it. Defeated again, he turns to *the rest of her offspring, who keep the commandments of God and hold to the testimony of Jesus* — the church. The chapter ends pointing forward to chapter 13, where the dragon's earthly proxies will appear."
